value.value: A membrane glycoprotein complex with aspartyl proteinase and metalloproteinase activity which is expressed in the gut. An example of this is found in the nematode Haemonchus contortus.
A protein complex containing a secreted Wnt protein associated with its receptor, Frizzled (Fz), and co-receptor low density lipoprotein receptor-related protein 5 (LRP5) or LRP6.

definition.value: Given the number of Wnt proteins, Frizzled proteins and LRP proteins, many different trimeric complexes are likely to form.

label.value: protein transport along microtubule to spindle pole body

value.value: The directed movement of a protein along a microtubule to the spindle pole body, mediated by motor proteins.
The attachment of a lytic vacuole to the endoplasmic reticulum, which may facilitate exchange of metabolites between the organelles.
Binding to methionine-initiator methionine tRNA.

definition.value: An example of this is eukaryotic initiation factor 2 complex, which binds the methionyl-initiator methionine tRNA during ternary complex formation. The non-acylated tRNA is not bound.

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lectin stimulus. A lectin is a carbohydrate-binding protein, highly specific for binding sugar moieties.

definition.value: This term refers to endogenous (evolved) responses to lectins (endogenous or exogenous), it does not cover the events that happen due to lectin toxicity.

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an endothelin stimulus. Endothelin is any of three secretory vasoconstrictive peptides (endothelin-1, -2, -3).

A cyclin dependent kinase (CDK) complex that contains a kinase subunit and a regulatory cyclin subunit. An example of this complex in budding yeast S. cerevisiae consists of the Pho85 kinase and the Pho80 cyclin.
A protein complex that cleaves ubiquitin from specific substrates. In the budding yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae, this complex consists of Ubp3p and Bre5p.
A protein complex that resides in the inner nuclear membrane and anchors telomeres to the nuclear envelope. In fission yeast, it is composed of Bqt3 and Bqt4.

The multiplication or reproduction of acinar cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. An acinar cell is a secretory cell that is grouped together with other cells of the same type to form grape-shaped clusters known as acini (singular acinus).

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a growth hormone-releasing hormone stimulus. Growth hormone-releasing hormone regulates the release of growth hormone, as well as some pancreatic proteins, and possibly other proteins.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a gastrin stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a chemokine stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a chemokine stimulus.
A protein complex that is involved in the assembly of the V-ATPase complex. In the budding yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae, this complex consists of Vma12p and Vma22p.

label.value: vascular associated smooth muscle cell proliferation

value.value: The multiplication or reproduction of vascular smooth muscle cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. A vascular smooth muscle cell is a non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cell found lining the blood vessels.
The side of the nuclear pore complex (NPC) that faces the nucleoplasm.
The side of the nuclear pore complex (NPC) that faces the cytoplasm.

A heterodimeric complex that functions as a GTPase-Activating Protein (GAP) Complex for members of the Rag family of GTPases. In the budding yeast, this complex contains Lst4 and Lst7, while the orthologous mammalian complex contains follicular (FLCN) and either follicular interacting protein 1 (FNIP1) or FNIP2.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a gastrin stimulus.

A complex formed by the association of Cdc13 (CTC1 in mammals) with Stn1 in yeast (OBFC1 in mammals) and Ten1 protein (also TEN1 in mammals) with single-stranded telomeric DNA. The CST complex plays a role in telomere protection.

Any process that reduces or removes the toxicity of copper ions in a cell. These include transport of copper cations away from sensitive areas and to compartments or complexes whose purpose is sequestration.
The modification of rRNA structure by addition of an acetyl group to rRNA. An acetyl group is CH3CO-, derived from acetic [ethanoic] acid.
Catalysis of the reaction: acetyl-CoA + cytidine = CoA + N4-acetylcytidine. The cytidine is within the polynucleotide chain of an rRNA.
The posttranscriptional addition of one or more acetyl groups to specific residues in an RNA molecule.
Catalysis of the reaction: 2-polyprenyl-6-hydroxyphenol + S-adenosyl-L-methionine = 2-polyprenyl-6-methoxyphenol + S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + H+.
Binding to a histone H4 in which the lysine residue at position 20 has been modified by trimethylation.
Binding to a netrin receptor.
The cell cycle process in which sister chromatid arms are physically detached from each other during mitosis.
The cell cycle process in which chromosome arm chromatin structure is compacted prior to and during mitosis in eukaryotic cells.
The cell cycle process in which centromere chromatin structure is compacted prior to and during mitosis.

label.value: regulation of protein localization to cell cortex of cell tip

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to cell cortex of cell tip.

label.value: protein localization to cell cortex of cell tip

value.value: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, the cell cortex of the cell tip.

A constriction site at the junction of the plasma, flagellar and flagellar pocket membranes where the flagellum emerges from the cell body. Observed in some unicellular eukaryotic species such as Chlamydomonas, Giardia and Trypanosoma.

definition.value: Note that a 'flagellar collar' is described in Choanoflagellates, but this is different from the ciliary pocket collar found e.g. in Giardia; in Choanoflagellates, a single apical flagellum is surrounded by a collar of 30-40 microvilli.

value.value: The cell pole distal from the most recent cell division.
The cell pole proximal to the most recent cell division.
A macromolecular complex that contains both RNA and protein molecules.

A small, flexible, finger-like projection of cytoplasm containing an array of microtubles and located near the flagellar pores in some photosynthetic as well as nonphotosynthetic dinoflagellate species. Its functions are not fully understood, but it has been associated with feeding behavior (phagotrophy).

definition.value: The term name refers to a taxonomic group to make the label unique with respect to similarly-named anatomical structures.

value.value: A cilium-like cell projection emanating from the inner segment and running alongside the outer segment of photoreceptors.
A protein complex that contains beta-catenin and a member of the T-cell factor (TCF)/lymphoid enhancer binding factor (LEF) family of transcription factors.

A multiprotein protein complex containing membrane-localized Wnt receptors and cytosolic protein complexes, which is capable of transmitting the Wnt signal. Contains at least a Wnt protein, LRP5 or LRP6, a member of the Frizzled (Fz) family, Axin and and a Dishevelled (DVL) protein.

definition.value: Within the Wnt signalosome, beta-catenin phosphorylation is inhibited through internalization of the signalosome complex, resulting in the sequestration of GSK3-beta into multi-vesicular bodies. No longer phosphorylated and targeted for degradation, beta-catenin is free to enter the nucleus and modulate downstream transcription.

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating lowered oxygen tension combined with low atmospheric pressure. Hypoxia is defined as a decline in O2 levels below normoxic levels of 20.8 - 20.95% and hypobaric is defined as atmospheric pressure below 0.74 atm (greater than 2,500 m above sea level).

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of exposure to aversive or demanding psychological and social conditions that tax or exceed the behavioral resources of the organism.
The plasma membrane that is part of the head section of a sperm cell.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of an ascospore wall.
The outermost layers of the spore wall, as described in Schizosaccharomyces pombe.
The cytoplasm of an ovum.

label.value: double-strand break repair involved in meiotic recombination

value.value: The repair of double-strand breaks in DNA via homologous and nonhomologous mechanisms to reform a continuous DNA helix that contributes to reciprocal meiotic recombination.
The binding activity of a molecule that brings together a proteasome complex and a nuclear inner membrane, to maintain the nuclear membrane localization of the proteasome.
